Musharraf has carefully prepared the plan of attack, without details of the then Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif. He was supported and supported by Lt. Gen. Mohammed Aziz. I have very few memories of him. I have more memories of what it feels like to have no father. I also remember how much I hated Pakistan and Pakistanis for killing my father. I also hated Muslims because I thought all Muslims were Pakistanis. When I was 6 years old, I tried to stab a woman in a Burkha. For some strange reason, I thought she was responsible for my father's death. My mother stopped me and made me understand that Pakistan did not kill my father, war killed him. It took a while for me to know. I have learned to let go of my hatred. It was not easy, but it is not difficult. If I can, then you too. Today I am also a soldier, just like my father. I fight for peace between India and Pakistan. Because if there was no war between us, my dad would still be here. I'm making this video because I want governments in both countries to stop pretending they solve the problem. If France and Germany can become friends after 2 world wars, if Japan and the US can leave their past behind and work towards progress, why can not we? The majority of regular Indians and Pakistanis want peace, not war. I doubt the caliber of leadership of both nations. We can not dream of becoming a First World leader in the Third World. Please pull up your socks. Talk to each other and do the work. Enough state-sponsored terrorism. Enough state-sponsored spies. Enough state-sponsored hatred. On both sides of the border enough people have died. Enough is enough. I want to live in a world where there is no Gurmehar Kaur's who miss her father. Kevin Gaskin You are welcome to search the Bill of Rights, the US Constitution, and the Declaration of Independence, but you will not find anything about "Church and State Separation" in any of them. Thomas Jefferson wrote a letter to the Danbury Baptist Association in 1802 to answer a letter from them, asking why he would not proclaim National Lenten and Thanksgiving Days, as Washington and Adams had previously done. The letter contains the phrase "wall of separation between church and state", which has led to the erroneous "short cut" for the founding clause (US Constitution, Bill of Rights, Amendment I, Article III) that we use today. "Why do I have religious freedom ...?" The answer lay in the congressional papers that relate to our constitution, as we know it today. The process of preparing the First Amendment made the intentions of the founders clear. Because before the final text was passed, the First Amendment went through almost a dozen different iterations and in-depth discussions. "We do not want in America what we had in Britain: we do not want a denomination to rule the nation. We will not all be Catholics or Anglicans or any other denomination. We want God's principles, but we do not want a nation to rule the nation. "This intention was understood as evidence of court rulings under the First Amendment Act. In 1799, the court declared, "Through our form of government, the Christian religion is the established religion; and all the sects and denominations of Christians are equal. "One must realize that our founding fathers sought" religious freedom "because of the oppressive authority of the Roman Catholic Church. It was not just Great Britain, but the largest part of Europe, which came under the incredible authority of Roman Catholicism. Our founding fathers wanted to recognize the many denominations of Christianity. In addition, they intended to recognize each face value equally, rather than granting control powers by a single face value. Therein lay the misinterpretation of the reckless abbreviation known as "Separation of Church and State." A more accurate statement is likely to be "separation of church and state denominations." Such an interpretation is fully supported by the Congress papers relating to the GDR. Statement: "We do not want in America what we had in the UK: we do not want a denomination to rule the nation. We will not all be Catholics or Anglicans or any other denomination. We want God's principles, but we do not want a nation to rule the nation. "As for the statement," Most of our founding fathers were agnostics, "that's simply not true. It is a sweeping statement proclaimed by those who speak out against religion in general. Yes, at that time there were agnostics, but they were not nearly as common as claimed. Thomas Paine was an Anglo-American political activist, philosopher, political theorist and revolutionary. Although he is considered one of our founding fathers, he was shunned because of his well-known agnostic convictions. John Adams is also a mistakenly accused agnostic. Here is a quote from President Adams regarding Thomas Paine; "The Christian religion, especially the religions that ever prevailed or existed in antiquity or modern times, is the religion of wisdom, virtue, justice and humanity, let the Blackguard Paine say what it wants." The Central Statistical Office (CSO) changed the way GDP is calculated and said it was necessary to keep an eye on global practices. As a result, India surpassed China and became the fastest growing economy. In 2013-2014, our economy grew 6.9% instead of 4.7%, as previously indicated by the CSO data. Even the country's most important economic adviser, Arvind Subramanian, said, "I am stunned by the new GDP growth figures. The revised figures show that GDP growth increased from 4.7% to 5.1% from 2012 to 2013 and from 5% to 5.9% from 2013 to 2012. This means an acceleration of GDP growth by 1.9 percentage points in 2013-2014, only by comparing the new numbers over time.
